explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro/check may expand to code that affects control flow (returns, longjmp) or could itself contain loops; must inspect to ensure it does not contain/affect for-loop clauses.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain records; may expand into expressions or function calls (e.g. OS_ObjectIndexFromToken) that include iterations or side effects relevant to loop-clause analysis.
- OS_global_module_table, OS_module_table: Objects referenced via OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; their accessor implementation might iterate or use indices — need to see how token is converted to an index and whether any loops/side-effects occur.
- OS_common_record_t, OS_module_internal_record_t, OS_module_prop_t, OS_object_token_t, osal_id_t: Type definitions for the objects manipulated in the function. Needed to determine whether fields used in expressions are simple scalars/arrays and whether any of them could serve as loop counters or be modified by called functions.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Called to obtain a token; its implementation may perform iterations or modify objects (including the token) — inspect to ensure it does not introduce for-loops or side effects that would affect any surrounding for-loop clauses.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Potentially invoked via macros to obtain array indices; its implementation may include loops or side effects that matter to the MISRA for-loop rule.
- OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl: Called while holding token and passed module_prop; must inspect this callee for any for-loops or modifications of objects that would be used as loop counters in any for statement in the caller.
- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token; its implementation may include loops or modify objects (e.g. token) — needed to verify absence of problematic loop-related side effects.
- memset, strncpy: Standard library routines used in this function; these may be implemented as macros or inline code containing loops in some environments — include to confirm they are not macros/inline for this build and do not introduce for-loops or side effects that would invalidate loop-clause analysis.

Rationale: The MISRA clause requires analyzing the three clauses of any for statement and also treating the behavior of functions called from the for-body as part of that body. Even though OS_ModuleInfo contains no explicit for loop, macros or callees could expand to or contain for-loops or have side effects on objects that could act as loop counters. The listed symbols are the minimal set needed to inspect macro expansions, type layouts, and callee implementations to decide compliance.
